Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents a huge bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had continued to balloon due to falling house prices.
Now that the government fully guarantees Fannie and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that is not covered by the insufficient financial resources of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the most openly capitalist country in the world?
Do not the venerable principles of capitalism include that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers now have to suffer the consequences of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly defined.
But they are not.
Especially unclear is whether the bailout will actually cost US taxpayers anything in the long run. It might prevent further systemic effects that would cripple the financial sector and thus the world economy.
Just because systemic effects are hard to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
Moreover, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being backed by an implicit guarantee from the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the failure of the US government to take rescue action could undermine confidence in government securities - and because they are associated with these, also in other financial instruments.
The problems reach far beyond the US economy.
The world economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative rises and falls in asset values, bringing into the equation questions of trust, but also of fairness.
In many other countries as well, similar housing sector highs are currently coming to an end, and they may be facing the same sufferings - and the same moral dilemmas - that the US economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not only the housing markets.
The stock markets are as well.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose 5 times between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose 5 times in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar soaring and crashes of stock markets have occurred in many other countries.
As long as they held on, the boom phases preceding these crashes led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a loss of confidence could grip the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts would be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of confidence, no way to predict how people will react when help fails to arrive in the face of collapsing markets.
People's reactions to these events depend on their feelings and their sense of justice.
The described soaring and crashes have caused a major redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested on the stock market or in the housing market did well or poorly depending on their timing.
People will judge the fairness of these results based on what was told to them and what silent promises they derived from it.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
Unfortunately, there is no way to find out.
Policy can only react in general and cannot treat each case individually.
We know that the economic growth of recent times has been spectacular in many countries.
But were the capital investments in their markets sold too expensively?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere led people to believe that the boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It is certain that, although there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – most of the losers in this game are not gnawing at the hunger cloth.
Yet we cannot carelessly conclude from this that one should unconditionally let all their losses stand.
The gnawing problem is one of "trust and faith".
Nations' economies flourish only when "trust and faith" prevail.
The current situation, in which speculative flights have driven the world economy – and now, after their collapse, are driving it into recession – suggests that people who have promoted certain capital investments have done so contrary to trust and faith.
Take the investors who purchased bonds from Fannie and Freddie.
Although the US government never officially promised to bail them out in a crisis, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
This agency, however, never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
Government officials never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is beginning to discover capitalism and its power to transform economies.
Yet capitalism relies on trust and good faith.
An unfair treatment can be deadly for economic growth, because it means that people lose trust in companies and are therefore less willing to provide them with their valuable capital and labor.
Is such an outcome morally preferable to a bailout?
